(448, 1, 'admin', '/admin/Faq/edit', 'faq-编辑', '{\"id\":\"1\",\"enable\":\"1\",\"title\":\"this is faq 1\",\"en_title\":\"Why are glass-lined tubes used as heat exchanger tubes in shell and tube heat exchangers?  Glass-lined tubes, also referred to as glass lined, glass lining, or enameled glass, are commonly employed in shell and tube heat exchangers. The glass lining on the inner surface of the tubes acts as a barrier between corrosive process fluids and the metal tubes, preventing fluid corrosion or erosion of the tubes. This makes them particularly suitable for corrosive fluids such as acids, alkalis, or salt solutions. In addition to their corrosion resistance, glass-lined tubes also exhibit good thermal conductivity, enabling efficient heat transfer between process fluids and the heat exchange medium. This makes them well-suited for applications where heat transfer efficiency is crucial, such as chemical processing, pharmaceuticals, and food and beverage production. Overall, the use of glass-lined tubes, glass lining, or enameled glass in shell and tube heat exchangers offers numerous advantages, including improved durability, extended service life, and enhanced heat transfer performance, contributing to reduced maintenance and operational costs.\",\"content\":\"\",\"en_content\":\"\",\"rich_content\":\"Glass-lined tubes, also referred to as glass lined, glass lining, or enameled glass, are commonly employed in shell and tube heat exchangers. The glass lining on the inner surface of the tubes acts as a barrier between corrosive process fluids and the metal tubes, preventing fluid corrosion or erosion of the tubes. This makes them particularly suitable for corrosive fluids such as acids, alkalis, or salt solutions. In addition to their corrosion resistance, glass-lined tubes also exhibit good thermal conductivity, enabling efficient heat transfer between process fluids and the heat exchange medium. This makes them well-suited for applications where heat transfe