(645, 1, 'admin', '/admin/Faq/edit', 'faq-编辑', '{\"id\":\"18\",\"enable\":\"1\",\"title\":\"\",\"en_title\":\"What are the advantages of our products over metallic shell and tube heat exchangers?\",\"content\":\"\",\"en_content\":\"Repicea Said,\",\"rich_content\":\"1\",\"en_rich_content\":\"Our glass-lined and silicon carbide shell and tube heat exchangers offer several distinct advantages over metallic shell and tube heat exchangers. These advantages include:Superior Corrosion Resistance: Our glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers are highly resistant to corrosion. Glass lining provides exceptional resistance to a wide range of corrosive chemicals, making it suitable for handling aggressive fluids. Silicon carbide, on the other hand, offers excellent corrosion resistance to acids, alkalis, and other harsh chemicals. This corrosion resistance ensures longer equipment life and reduces the risk of leaks or contamination.High Thermal Efficiency: Glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers have excellent thermal conductivity properties. This enables efficient heat transfer, resulting in enhanced performance and reduced energy consumption. The efficient heat transfer capability of our heat exchangers translates into cost savings and improved process efficiency.Chemical Inertness: Glass-lined and silicon carbide materials are chemically inert, which means they do not react with or contaminate the fluids being processed. This is especially important in applications where product purity is critical, such as in pharmaceutical, food, or chemical industries. The use of our heat exchangers helps ensure the integrity and purity of the processed fluids.Smooth Surface and Easy Cleanability: The smooth surfaces of glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers minimize fouling and deposits, making them easier to clean and maintain. The absence of surface irregularities or roughness reduces the risk of fouling, which can negatively impact heat transfer efficiency. This ease of cleaning and maintenance contributes to longer equipment life and reduced downtime.Wide Range of Operating Conditions: Our heat exchangers can withstand a broad range of operating conditions, including high temperatures and pressures. Glass-lined heat exchangers can typically handle temperatures up to 200°C (392°F) and pressures up to 6 bar (87 psi), while silicon carbide heat exchangers offer even higher temperature and pressure capabilities. This versatility makes our heat exchangers suitable for a wide range of applications and industries.Longevity and Durability: Glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers are known for their durability and long service life. The robust construction and corrosion resistance properties ensure the equipment&#039;s longevity, minimizing the need for frequent replacements or repairs. This results in cost savings and improved overall operational reliability.By choosing our glass-lined and silicon carbide shell and tube heat exchangers, you can benefit from these advantages and enhance the performance, reliability, and longevity of your heat transfer processes.If you have any other questions, please click the pinecone on the right side of the screen and feel free to contact our product experts for a more comprehensive answer. \"}', '114.217.196.6', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/108.0.5359.95 Safari/537.36', 1685514473),
(646, 1, 'admin', '/admin/Faq/edit', 'faq-编辑', '{\"id\":\"19\",\"enable\":\"1\",\"title\":\"\",\"en_title\":\"Which users are not suitable for metallic shell and tube heat exchangers and are suitable for glass lined and silicon carbide shell and tube heat exchangers?\",\"content\":\"\",\"en_content\":\"Repicea Said,\",\"rich_content\":\"1\",\"en_rich_content\":\"Glass-lined and silicon carbide shell and tube heat exchangers are particularly well-suited for users who encounter certain conditions or have specific requirements that make metallic heat exchangers less suitable. Here are some instances where glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers excel:Corrosive Environments: If your application involves handling corrosive fluids or operating in corrosive environments, glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers are excellent choices. They provide exceptional resistance to a wide range of corrosive chemicals, including acids, alkalis, and other aggressive substances. Metallic heat exchangers may be prone to corrosion and require additional corrosion protection measures or frequent replacements in such conditions.High Purity Applications: In industries such as pharmaceutical, food and beverage, and semiconductor manufacturing, maintaining product purity is critical. Glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers offer the advantage of being chemically inert, ensuring there is no contamination or reaction with the processed fluids. This is particularly beneficial for applications where product integrity and purity are paramount.Thermal Efficiency Requirements: If your process demands high thermal efficiency and effective heat transfer, glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers deliver superior performance. These materials have excellent thermal conductivity, enabling efficient heat transfer and reducing energy consumption. As a result, they are well-suited for applications where optimizing heat transfer efficiency is essential.Easy Cleanability: The smooth surfaces of glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers minimize fouling and make them easier to clean. This is advantageous in applications where scaling, fouling, or deposit buildup can occur. The smooth surfaces of these heat exchangers promote good fluid flow and reduce the risk of performance degradation due to fouling, ultimately reducing maintenance efforts and downtime.Wide Temperature and Pressure Ranges: Glass-lined and silicon carbide heat exchangers can operate in a wide range of temperatures and pressures. While metallic heat exchangers may have limitations in terms of temperature and pressure capabilities, glass-lined heat exchangers can typically handle temperatures up to 200°C (392°F) and pressures up to 6 bar (87 psi), while silicon carbide heat exchangers offer even higher temperature and pressure capabilities.It&#039;s important to assess your specific application requirements, operating conditions, and the nature of the fluids being processed when selecting the most suitable heat exchanger. If you have any other questions, please click the pinecone on the right side of the screen and feel free to contact our product experts for a more comprehensive answer.\"}', '114.217.196.6', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/108.0.5359.95 Safari/537.36', 1685514569),
(647, 1, 'admin', '/admin/Faq/edit', 'faq-编辑', '{\"id\":\"20\",\"enable\":\"1\",\"title\":\"\",\"en_title\":\"What chemical materials require the use of glass lining and silicon carbide shell and tube shell and tube heat exchangers?\",\"content\":\"\",\"en_content\":\"Repicea Said,\",\"rich_content\":\"1\",\"en_rich_content\":\"Glass lining and silicon carbide shell and tube heat exchangers are particularly well-suited for handling various chemical materials that may pose corrosion or contamination risks to metallic heat exchangers. Here are some examples of chemical materials that often require the use of glass lining or silicon carbide in heat exchangers:Strong Acids: Glass lining and silicon carbide are highly resistant to strong acids, such as sulfuric acid (H2SO4), hydrochloric acid (HCl), nitric acid (HNO3), and phosphoric acid (H3PO4). These materials can handle the corrosive nature of these acids without degradation or contamination.Alkalis: Glass lining and silicon carbide are well-suited for alkali applications, including sodium hydroxide (NaOH), potassium hydroxide (KOH), and other caustic solutions. They offer excellent resistance to the alkaline properties of these substances.Organic Solvents: Certain organic solvents, such as toluene, acetone, and methanol, can be corrosive to metallic heat exchangers. Glass lining and silicon carbide provide excellent chemical resistance to a wide range of organic solvents, making them suitable for applications involving these materials.Halogens: Halogens like chlorine (Cl2) and bromine (Br2) can be highly corrosive to metallic surfaces. Glass lining and silicon carbide offer exceptional resistance to halogens, allowing safe handling of these substances without the risk of corrosion or contamination.Salts and Brines: Glass lining and silicon carbide heat exchangers can handle the corrosive effects of salt solutions and brines, including sodium chloride (NaCl) and potassium chloride (KCl). These materials are commonly used in various industrial processes and require corrosion-resistant heat exchangers.Aggressive Chemical Mixtures: In applications where chemical mixtures contain a combination of corrosive substances, glass lining and silicon carbide provide a reliable solution. They can withstand the corrosive effects of mixed chemical solutions and ensure the integrity of the heat exchanger.It&#039;s important to consider the specific concentration, temperature, and other operating conditions of the chemical materials to determine the most suitable heat exchanger material. Consulting with heat exchanger experts or manufacturers can help you identify the appropriate choice based on your chemical handling requirements.If you have any other questions, please click the pinecone on the right side of the screen and feel free to contact our product experts for a more comprehensive answer.\"}', '114.217.196.6', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/108.0.5359.95 Safari/537.36', 1685514725),
(648, 1, 'admin', '/admin/Faq/edit', 'faq-编辑', '{\"id\":\"21\",\"enable\":\"1\",\"title\":\"\",\"en_title\":\"Why is glass lining more suitable than alloys in corrosive environments?\",\"content\":\"\",\"en_content\":\"Repicea Said,\",\"rich_content\":\"1\",\"en_rich_content\":\"Glass lining is often more suitable than alloys in corrosive environments for several reasons:Superior Corrosion Resistance: Glass lining offers exceptional resistance to a wide range of corrosive chemicals, including strong acids, alkalis, and organic solvents. It forms a protective barrier between the corrosive environment and the base metal, preventing direct contact and minimizing the risk of corrosion. Alloys, while corrosion-resistant to some extent, may not provide the same level of resistance as glass lining when exposed to highly corrosive substances.Non-Reactive and Inert: Glass lining is chemically inert, meaning it does not react with or contaminate the fluids being processed. This is particularly important in applications where product purity is critical, such as in pharmaceutical or food industries. Alloys, on the other hand, may have trace amounts of reactive elements or impurities that could potentially affect the quality or integrity of the processed fluids.Homogeneous and Impermeable Surface: Glass lining forms a smooth and impermeable surface that is resistant to penetration by corrosive substances. This prevents corrosive agents from reaching the base metal, ensuring long-term corrosion resistance. Alloys, while resistant to corrosion, may have microscopic surface imperfections or pores that could allow corrosive substances to permeate and attack the base metal over time.Ease of Maintenance: Glass lining is relatively easy to clean and maintain. The smooth and non-porous surface of glass-lined equipment minimizes fouling and deposits, making cleaning more efficient. Alloys, especially those with complex surface structures or roughness, can be more challenging to clean and may require additional maintenance efforts.Cost-Effective Solution: Glass lining can be a cost-effective solution in corrosive environments. While alloys may offer corrosion resistance, they can be more expensive to manufacture and may require additional surface treatments or coatings to enhance their corrosion resistance. Glass lining provides a durable and reliable corrosion-resistant solution without the need for costly alloy materials or extensive surface treatments.It&#039;s important to consider the specific corrosive environment, process conditions, and requirements when selecting the most suitable material. If you have any other questions, please click the pinecone on the right side of the screen and feel free to contact our product experts for a more comprehensive answer.\"}', '114.217.196.6', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/108.0.5359.95 Safari/537.36', 1685514781),
(649, 1, 'admin', '/admin/Faq/edit', 'faq-编辑', '{\"id\":\"22\",\"enable\":\"1\",\"title\":\"\",\"en_title\":\"How to choose the inlet and outlet sizes of a shell and tube heat exchanger?\",\"content\":\"\",\"en_content\":\"Repicea Said,\",\"rich_content\":\"1\",\"en_rich_content\":\"Choosing the appropriate inlet and outlet sizes for a shell and tube heat exchanger involves considering several factors to ensure optimal performance and compatibility with your system. Here are some key considerations:Flow Rate: Determine the desired flow rate of the fluid passing through the heat exchanger. This information is typically specified by your process requirements or system design. It&#039;s important to select inlet and outlet sizes that can accommodate the required flow rate without causing excessive pressure drop or velocity.Pressure Drop: Evaluate the pressure drop constraints of your system. Excessive pressure drop can impact the overall system performance and efficiency. Consider the pressure limitations of the heat exchanger and the available pressure drop in your system when selecting the inlet and outlet sizes. This will help ensure the heat exchanger operates within the desired pressure range.Compatibility: Ensure that the inlet and outlet sizes of the heat exchanger are compatible with the piping system in your application. The sizes should match or be adaptable to the existing piping connections or requirements. Consider factors such as pipe diameter, flange size, and connection type (e.g., threaded, welded, flanged) to ensure proper installation and integration.Fluid Properties: Evaluate the properties of the fluid being processed in the heat exchanger, such as viscosity and density. Fluid properties can impact the pressure drop and flow characteristics within the heat exchanger. Consider the fluid&#039;s behavior and select appropriate inlet and outlet sizes to ensure efficient heat transfer and fluid handling.Future Expansion or Modifications: Consider any future expansion plans or potential modifications to your system. If you anticipate changes in the flow rate or system requirements, it may be beneficial to select slightly larger inlet and outlet sizes to allow for future flexibility and capacity.Ultimately, it is advisable to consult with heat exchanger experts or manufacturers who can provide guidance tailored to your specific requirements. They can help analyze your application needs, recommend suitable inlet and outlet sizes, and assist in selecting the most appropriate shell and tube heat exchanger for your application.If you have any other questions, please click the pinecone on the right side of the screen and feel free to contact our product experts for a more comprehensive answer.\"}', '114.217.196.6', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/108.0.5359.95 Safari/537.36', 1685514822),
