(660, 1, 'admin', '/admin/Faq/edit', 'faq-编辑', '{\"id\":\"32\",\"enable\":\"1\",\"title\":\"\",\"en_title\":\"Common corrosive liquids include:\",\"content\":\"\",\"en_content\":\"Repicea Said,\",\"rich_content\":\"1\",\"en_rich_content\":\"Common corrosive liquids include:Acids: Acids such as sulfuric acid, hydrochloric acid, nitric acid, and acetic acid are highly corrosive. They can cause damage to various materials, including metals.Alkalis: Strong alkaline substances like sodium hydroxide and potassium hydroxide can corrode materials. They are often used in industrial processes such as chemical manufacturing and water treatment.Salts: Certain salts, particularly those that are highly reactive, can be corrosive. Examples include ammonium chloride, sodium chloride, and calcium chloride.Oxidizing Agents: Strong oxidizing agents like hydrogen peroxide, chlorine, and bromine can cause corrosion when in contact with certain materials.Organic Solvents: Some organic solvents, such as concentrated ethanol or methanol, can be corrosive to certain materials.Seawater: Seawater contains various salts and minerals, which can lead to corrosion of metals and other materials.Industrial Chemicals: Numerous industrial chemicals used in manufacturing processes, such as solvents, detergents, and cleaning agents, can exhibit corrosive properties.It is important to consider the corrosive nature of these liquids when selecting materials for equipment like heat exchangers, where they may come into contact with such substances. Glass-lined and silicon carbide shell and tube heat exchangers are specifically designed to withstand the corrosive effects of many of these liquids, making them suitable choices for industries dealing with corrosive fluids.If you have any other questions, please click the pinecone on the right side of the screen and feel free to contact our experts at Repicea for a more comprehensive answer and personalized assistance.\"}', '114.217.196.6', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows